error.signature: cannot use type *v1.FooRequest as type *v2.FooRequest in argument to RegisterFooServer

verdict.summary: Generated protobuf Go code is out of sync with the .proto definitions or incompatible protobuf library versions are mixed. Commonly happens when client and server use different generated code versions.

dead_ends.action: Manually edit generated .pb.go files to fix type mismatches
dead_ends.why_fails: Generated files are overwritten on next protoc run — manual edits are lost and the underlying .proto mismatch remains

dead_ends.action: Mix google.golang.org/protobuf and github.com/golang/protobuf v1 APIs
dead_ends.why_fails: The two protobuf Go API versions generate incompatible types — mixing them causes type assertion failures

workarounds.action: Regenerate all protobuf Go code from the same .proto files
workarounds.how:
protoc --go_out=. --go-grpc_out=. proto/*.proto
Ensure all services use the same generated package.

workarounds.action: Pin protobuf library versions consistently across all modules
workarounds.how:
go get google.golang.org/protobuf@latest
go get google.golang.org/grpc@latest
go mod tidy
workarounds.condition: when using Go modules with multiple services

leads_to.condition: when server rejects requests due to proto schema mismatch

preceded_by.condition: when protobuf library version update causes checksum changes

frequently_confused_with.distinction: Protobuf mismatch specifically involves generated .pb.go types from different proto versions, while generic 'cannot use as type' is a general Go type system error.
